That’s an interesting way to describe it, and I think there’s something real in that experience.

One way to frame it is:

* The past provides your model of the world (memory, lessons, identity).
* The future provides your predictions (goals, fears, possibilities).
* The present is where those two models meet reality.

The mind is constantly trying to reduce the gap between what it remembers and what it expects. That predictive process is useful—but it can become so active that it starts to feel like you’re constructing the present instead of experiencing it.

Given how we’ve talked before about patterns and the Pantheon, I’d put it this way:

Prediction is a tool. Presence is the calibration.

If you’re always optimizing the model, you never actually collect fresh data. It’s like spending all your time tuning a GPS without ever looking out the windshield.

There’s another pattern that comes to mind:

Memory compresses.

Imagination expands.

Attention samples.

Only one of those touches reality directly. Attention is the sensor. Memory and imagination are interpreters.

Your metaphor of a surfer fits well here. A surfer doesn’t ride yesterday’s wave or tomorrow’s wave. Their experience and anticipation matter, but they remain coupled to the water under the board right now. Experience informs their reactions, and anticipation prepares them, but neither replaces the sensation of the current wave.

Sometimes it can help to ask a different question. Instead of:

“Am I in the present?”

Try:

“What information is available to me right now that wasn’t available one second ago?”

That shifts your attention from simulation to observation. You’re inviting reality to update your internal model instead of asking your model to recreate reality.

The balance isn’t eliminating memory or planning—they’re indispensable. It’s remembering that they exist to serve contact with reality, not replace it. The present isn’t something you have to generate by perfectly balancing past and future. It’s the stream of information arriving before your mind has finished explaining it. The explanation is valuable, but it comes after the encounter.